# Plan 006 — Background Audio Playback Test
#
# BEFORE USING THIS FILE:
# =======================
# 1. Replace "CHANGE_ME" in the BG line below with the actual HTTP URL of a
#    WAV file accessible from the ESP32 device over WiFi.
#
#    The WAV file MUST meet all of these requirements:
#      - Sample rate:   44100 Hz  (any other rate is rejected with an error log)
#      - Channels:      1 (mono) or 2 (stereo)
#      - Bit depth:     16-bit integer PCM  OR  32-bit IEEE float PCM
#      - Container:     Standard RIFF/WAVE (not RF64, not BWF extensible format 0xFFFE)
#      - Minimum length: 60 seconds recommended (the BG stream loops on EOF, but
#                         very short files loop frequently with a 200 ms gap each time)
#
#    Example replacements:
#      BG http://192.168.1.10:8000/rain.wav 0 25
#      BG https://your-server.example.com/audio/pad.wav 0 20
#      BG http://192.168.1.1:8080/meditation_pad.wav -10 30
#
#    Quick test server (run on your development machine in a directory that
#    contains a suitable WAV file):
#      python3 -m http.server 8000
#    Then set the BG URL to http://<your-machine-ip>:8000/<filename>.wav
#
# 2. Make sure the ESP32 is connected to WiFi (configured via wifi_manager).
#    If WiFi is not connected when the timeline starts, bg_player_start()
#    returns ESP_ERR_INVALID_STATE, BG is silenced, and a warning is logged.
#    The synthesized channels continue regardless.
#
# 3. To verify sdcard:// no-op behaviour (CONFIG_BG_SDCARD_ENABLED=n, default):
#    Replace the BG line with: BG sdcard://test.wav 0 30
#    Expected serial output:
#      E bg_player: BG: SD card support not enabled in this build
#              (CONFIG_BG_SDCARD_ENABLED=n). Ignoring BG entry: sdcard://test.wav
#    The synthesized channels below must still function normally.
#
# WHAT THIS TEST VERIFIES:
# ========================
#  - BG pre-roll: BG audio is audible BEFORE any synthesized tone fires
#  - BG continues underneath synthesized channels (separate post-mix stage)
#  - binaural beat pair (ch1 + ch2) with Plan 005 freq_r 7th-token syntax
#  - pink noise underlay (wave_type=5) mixed alongside BG
#  - synthesized channel fade-out while BG continues
#  - BG loops seamlessly at EOF (re-opens HTTP connection)
#  - bg_player_stop fade-out at timeline end (220-sample ramp, no click)
#
# EXPECTED SERIAL LOG SEQUENCE:
# ==============================
#  I config_parser: BG pre-roll: starting http://... pan=0.00 loudness=0.25
#  I bg_player: BG: HTTP streaming <N> bytes from 'http://...'
#  I bg_player: BG fade-in: target_loudness=0.25 ramp=220 samples
#  [synthesized channel entries fire at their scheduled times]
#  I bg_player: BG: EOF on 'http://...', re-opening for loop (iteration 2)
#  [... loop continues ...]
#  I bg_player: BG fade-out complete, stopping producer task
#
# HEADROOM NOTE:
# ==============
#  At the loudness levels below the total peak is:
#    BG = 0.25 + ch1+ch2 binaural = 0.50 (inv_n_active) + ch3 noise = 0.30
#    Theoretical peak = 1.05  (just above 0 dBFS)
#  The existing int16 clamp in audio_test.c absorbs this without audible
#  distortion at these modest levels. If you increase any loudness values,
#  keep the sum of BG loudness + sum of active synthesized channel amplitudes
#  below 100 to avoid clipping.
#
# ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# === Background audio (pre-roll — starts BEFORE any timeline event) ===
# Replace CHANGE_ME with your actual HTTP URL (see instructions above)
BG http://CHANGE_ME/path/to/test.wav 0 25

# === Section 1 (t=0-7s): short 200 Hz tone — verify BG continues underneath ===
# ch0: 200 Hz sine, centred, 50% amplitude, 0 pan, wave_type=0 (sine)
A 2000 200 -100 50 0 0
A 7000 200 -100 0 0 0

# === Section 2 (t=8-14s): binaural pair using Plan 005 freq_r 7th-token syntax ===
# ch1: left ear  200 Hz
# ch2: right ear 208 Hz  →  8 Hz alpha-range binaural beat
A 8000 200 -100 50 0 1 200
A 8000 200 100 50 0 2 208
A 14000 200 -100 0 0 1
A 14000 200 100 0 0 2

# === Section 3 (t=15-30s): pink noise underlay alongside BG — verify mix stack ===
# ch3: pink noise (wave_type=5), centred, 30% amplitude
# 9-token form: A <time_ms> <freq_hz> <pan> <amplitude> <mod_depth> <channel> <freq_r> <wave_type>
A 15000 0 0 30 0 3 0 5
A 30000 0 0 0 0 3 0 5

# === Section 4 (t=31-35s): all synthesized channels off, BG still playing ===
# (Nothing needed — ch0-3 already ramp to 0 above.  BG loops on.)

# === End of test (t=35s): silence all channels; timeline stop will call bg_player_stop ===
A 35000 200 -100 0 0 0
